  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If you are selling a property in Brisbane in 2027, more than nine in ten buyers will encounter your home online before they ever set foot in it. The photos in your listing are not just marketing material; they are the first impression your property makes, and in most cases they determine whether a buyer adds your home to their inspection list or scrolls past. Choosing professional photography is not a cosmetic upgrade. It is the most important marketing decision you will make during your campaign.</p>

      <p>The difference between a professional photographer and a good phone camera is not about resolution. It is about technique, equipment, and experience in a specific genre of photography that most people rarely think about. Understanding what a professional does differently helps you evaluate what your agent is offering and why certain shoots produce results that others do not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a professional real estate photographer does differently</h2>
      <p>Wide-angle lenses are the most visible difference. A standard phone camera shows you roughly what your eye sees standing in the room. A professional wide-angle lens captures more of the space in a single frame, which lets buyers understand the full layout and proportions rather than piecing together a series of narrow shots. This is not about making rooms look bigger than they are; it is about giving buyers accurate information about the full space.</p>

      <p>HDR processing addresses one of the most common technical problems in property photography: the contrast between a bright outdoor view through windows and a darker interior. A single camera exposure cannot capture both correctly, so untreated shots either blow out the windows or underexpose the room. Professional photographers bracket their exposures and blend them in post-production, so buyers can see both the interior clearly and the garden or view through the windows. This is standard practice, and the difference in the final images is significant.</p>

      <p>Composition is the skill that separates a technically competent property photograph from one that genuinely sells the home. A good photographer reads the room before they set up, identifying the angle that best communicates the space, leads the eye through the frame, and highlights the features a buyer will care about. The choice of whether to shoot from a high or low camera position, how much of the ceiling to include, and what to leave out of the frame entirely are judgment calls that take experience to make consistently well.</p>

      <p>Timing also matters. Early morning light and late afternoon light are softer and warmer than midday sun, which produces harsh shadows and flat colour in exterior shots. Most professionals schedule their shoots around the best available light for the property's orientation, and experienced agents factor this into the photography booking rather than just finding the nearest available slot.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Drone photography and when it adds value</h2>
      <p>Aerial photography has become standard for properties with meaningful land, outdoor areas, or a location that benefits from being seen in context. For larger blocks in Brisbane's inner east, a drone shot communicates block size, roof condition, and proximity to parks, waterways, or transport in a way that no ground-level photograph can. Buyers who are comparing multiple properties often make their shortlists based on aerial shots because they resolve the questions about space and setting that ground-level photos cannot answer.</p>

      <p>For smaller lots or inner-city properties where block size is not a key selling point, drone photography is less essential. The value is in communicating what is genuinely there: a generous 600 to 800 square metre block in Morningside or Bulimba is worth showing from the air. A standard 300 square metre terrace lot is not improved by aerial photography, and artificially including it can make the block appear smaller than it reads at ground level.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Twilight photography: when dusk makes a difference</h2>
      <p>A twilight or dusk shoot is worth considering for properties with pools, outdoor entertaining areas, or strong street presence. The combination of warm interior light, blue sky, and lit outdoor spaces creates images that are visually distinctive in a listing full of daytime shots. Buyers scrolling through results are more likely to stop on a twilight image, which improves click-through rates on portals and opens the listing to buyers who might have continued past it.</p>

      <p>Twilight photography works best for properties where the outdoor areas are genuinely strong and where the exterior photographs well at night. It is less effective for properties with modest outdoor spaces or where the night-time appearance adds little to the daytime story.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What professional photography costs in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>For a standard Brisbane home across ground and first floor, professional photography typically costs between $400 and $800. Adding drone photography is usually an additional $200 to $400. A twilight or dusk shoot adds a further $200 to $400 on top of the daytime package. These costs are typically included in the vendor paid advertising (VPA) budget your agent will recommend as part of the overall marketing plan, rather than charged separately.</p>

      <p>The cost of professional photography is modest relative to the sale price of any Brisbane property. A campaign that generates one additional inspection, or that shortens your days on market by one week, will typically return far more than the cost of the photography. The question is not whether to invest in professional photography but which package suits your property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to prepare your property for the photographer</h2>
      <p>The best photography in the world cannot compensate for a property that is not ready to be photographed. Before the photographer arrives, every surface should be cleared of personal items and clutter, including benchtops, dining tables, and bathroom vanities. Cars should be moved from the driveway and street out front. Lawns and gardens should be freshly mowed and tidied. Bins should be put away. All curtains and blinds should be open to maximise natural light, and every light in the house should be turned on, including lamps, to create warmth in interior shots.</p>

      <p>These are not cosmetic details. Cluttered benchtops and closed blinds are among the most common reasons good properties have mediocre photos. A property that is fully prepared for photography on the scheduled day will produce images that are noticeably better than one that is photographed in its everyday condition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Review the photos before the listing goes live</h2>
      <p>You know your property better than the photographer does. Before your agent publishes the listing, ask to review the photos and provide feedback. If a shot does not represent a room accurately, or if an important feature of the property has been missed or poorly framed, flag it. A professional photographer will typically reshoot or replace specific images. Once the listing is live, the photos are what buyers see first and form their initial impression from. They are worth getting right before launch, not after.</p>

